Task #48 — Fix Mark's State 2 'Brief Consistency Helper' visibility

Original task: User reported they couldn't see the State 2 minimised
Mark tile ("Brief Consistency Helper") in the Preview app. Root cause:
when a study is created via "New Research", MG/PC/TA defaults are
pre-filled, so auto_ben_precheck immediately marks qa_status =
'precheck_passed'. Under the previous derive_ui_phase() logic that
counted as STEP_3_EXECUTION_READY and the Mark tile was hidden
entirely — so users effectively never saw State 2.

Per the Prompt 6 spec, "execution readiness" should mean the study
has actually been started (status moved out of 'draft'), not merely
that the brief currently passes precheck. This was also flagged as
the non-blocking comment in the most recent code review for #45.

Changes:
- artifacts/brainstorm/app.py: derive_ui_phase() now reaches
  STEP_3_EXECUTION_READY only when status is not in ('draft',). A
  passing precheck while still in draft now resolves to
  STEP_2_ANCHORS so the minimised Brief Consistency Helper stays
  visible right up until the user starts the study. The /mark-
  alignment-check phase guard reuses the helper unchanged, so it
  now correctly accepts passing-precheck draft studies.
- artifacts/brainstorm/test_prompt6_mark_presence.py: derivation
  unit case for precheck_passed-in-draft now expects STEP_2_ANCHORS;
  alignment-check route test drops the ta="" workaround it needed
  under the old logic; integration State 3 test renamed to assert
  the precheck-passed-in-draft case stays in State 2 (true State 3
  is unreachable via the configure render — that path redirects to
  view_output for non-draft studies — and is covered by the helper
  unit test).
- replit.md: Prompt 6 entry rewritten to describe the corrected
  mapping.

Tests: 12/12 passing (test_prompt6_mark_presence + test_prompt5_continuity).

Out of scope (untouched): Mark replies, system prompts, telemetry
behaviour, precheck logic, MG/PC/TA pre-fill behaviour, V1A
brainstorm_v1_replit_singlepage_pack/ files, brainstorm.db.
